---
import Base from '@/layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base title="About" description="How What We Know works, who builds it, and why it's free.">
  <section class="about">
    <div class="container">
      <h1 class="animate-fade-up">About this project</h1>

      <div class="about-body stagger">
        <p class="lead">What We Know is a free, community-sourced reference for trans people navigating transition in the UK. It exists because the information people need is scattered across dozens of platforms, often contradictory, and hard to verify.</p>

        <h2>What this is</h2>
        <p>Each topic page brings together what clinical guidelines say, what the community says, and where people disagree — with every claim sourced. We don't pretend there's consensus where there isn't, and we don't hide disagreements.</p>

        <p>This is not medical advice. It's a starting point for understanding what's out there, so you can make informed decisions with your healthcare provider — or on your own, if the system has let you down.</p>

        <h2>How content is created</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>We gather information</strong> from clinical guidelines (WPATH, Endocrine Society, NHS), published research (PubMed), community resources (GenderKit, TransHub, Transfeminine Science), and public discussion spaces (Reddit, forums).</li>
          <li><strong>We synthesise it</strong> into clear, plain-English summaries — identifying consensus, disagreement, and gaps in knowledge.</li>
          <li><strong>We review it.</strong> Every page is reviewed by a real person before it goes live. When new information changes the picture, we update and note what changed.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>We use AI tools to help with research (searching papers, cross-referencing sources). We do not use AI to write content. Everything you read was written and reviewed by a human.</p>

        <h2>Who builds this</h2>
        <p>This project is built by Charlie Buckley, a trans woman based in Brighton. It started as part of a broader health app project and became its own thing because the information problem was too urgent to wait.</p>

        <p>We're looking for a clinical advisor to review medical content. If you're a healthcare professional working in trans health and interested in helping, please <a href="mailto:charlie@harperautomation.co.uk">get in touch</a>.</p>

        <h2>Why it's free</h2>
        <p>Because paywalling health information for a community that's already underserved is wrong. This will always be free.</p>

        <h2>Get involved</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Spot an error?</strong> Email <a href="mailto:charlie@harperautomation.co.uk">charlie@harperautomation.co.uk</a></li>
          <li><strong>Suggest a topic?</strong> Same email.</li>
          <li><strong>Want to help review content?</strong> Especially interested in hearing from healthcare professionals, researchers, and people with lived experience across different parts of the community.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-blue">
          <p><strong>This is early days.</strong> We're building in public. The first few topics are live, more are coming, and the whole thing will get better with community input.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .about {
    padding: var(--space-4xl) 0 var(--space-3xl);
  }

  .about h1 {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2xl);
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }
</style>
